column29: $SBUX CC: Q: In the US, what's happening with Nitro? Many stores selling out. A: Beverage growth was 80% of total sales growth in the quarter. We are making advancements behind the bar. We're installing new equipment. By early August, should be in 80% of the stores.
column30: $SBUX CC: In UberEats in the US is seeing food attach to a significant number of tickets. Haven't even started marketing. Encouraged when they expand it and get marketing dollars behind it.
column31: $SBUX CC: Gave software license to Brightloom in exchange for equity piece and board seat. SBUX tech team in-house can focus on company operated markets outside of China.
column32: $SBUX CC: Partnership with Alibaba has accelerated their digital flywheel in China. There are 10 large companies that operate most of SBUX stores in AMIA, Latin America. We need consistent way to delivery digital through Brightmoon.
column33: $SBUX!! 👍📈 Pretty sure I contributed a significant amount to their larger Q3 eps & revenue with my increased consumption of Nitro Cold Brew this summer. Yum!

column35: $SBUX CC: Significant long runway to attract new customers to Starbucks in China. We are creating a relationship with them. Customers for life.
column36: $SBUX CC: China is a tea drinking culture. We're introducing coffee, but sell tea as well. Many of the new stores are expanding into new cities. We're dramatically increasing the number of consumers being introduced to Starbucks.

column43: Starbucks smacked down naysayers everywhere. US whisper 4.5% & delivered 7%. 6% in China & 3% even in Europe. All that talk of fading brand relevance out the window $SBUX
column44: $SBUX CC: Starbucks Now is dedicated to mobile order/delivery in China. A unique concept they will further expand. Very pleased with how it's going and continue to monitor.
column45: $SBUX CC: Mobile pay in China: very bullish because of the digitally savvy Chinese customers. Rolled it out in late May. Now in 8 cities after it expanded it. Making sure to mitigate in-store bottlenecks they saw in the US mobile roll-out.
column46: $SBUX ftw! what it do babyyy 🤑
column47: $SBUX CC: In US look at 2 year comps. Because last year's was 1% in Q3. With 7% this year- two years of 8%. Highest 2 year comp in 8 quarters. Up over the 6% 2-year comp in Q2. Admits it was easy to lap last year's comp.
column48: $SBUX CC: In China delivery: available through Starbucks app and Alibaba platforms as well. Customers can engage more frequently. On track to 3,000 stores by end of fiscal 2019.
column49: $SBUX CC: In China delivery: slightly higher ticket than in the stores. Stronger in the morning. Usually food attached. Targeting 18 minute delivery time. Have strong partnership with $BABA and dedicated drivers to deliver SBUX products.
column50: $SBUX +67% since this tweet. ☕️  https://twitter.com/DougKass/status/1049725749685571584 …
column51: $SBUX CC: We had minimal marketing with UberEats through the trial period. We're pleased and we're moving forward. In China: consumer understands delivery. It has driven meaningful transaction lift.
column52: $SBUX CC: Delivery is moving slower in the US versus China as the US doesn't have a history of drink delivery. Markets included Seattle, SF, Boston, LA, DC and Miami. Launched 3 more in July. We're pleased with what we're seeing in our tickets.

How to choose your Starbuck Roasts by color:
- Blonde
- Medium

$SBUX $DNKN pic.twitter.com/ImcHOQEulY
column3:
Starbucks Pike Place med roast vs Blonde light roast — 
Pike tastes a bit stronger and bitter, 
Blonde is lighter, and smoother. 
Blonde Espresso is similar to other espresso: 
it's a lighter roast, so it's not as bitter. 
This makes it a universally enjoyable.

$SBUX $DNKN pic.twitter.com/3QfofmffAk
column4:
Starbucks COLD brewing is an incredibly versatile technique that brings out a smooth, mellow and delicately sweet taste in coffee. Fresh grounds are fully immersed in cool or room-temperature water and left undisturbed for hours. Without heat, less acid is extracted.

$SBUX $DNKN pic.twitter.com/XIaGRcdjs2
column5:
Starbucks POUR-OVER 
is a simple technique that produces a beautiful cup. To brew, hot water is gently poured over freshly ground coffee in a circular motion. As water passes through a filter holding a bed of grounds, nuanced flavors are extracted from the coffee.

$SBUX $DNKN pic.twitter.com/IDsD9StG1O
column6:
Starbucks SIPHON 
is a visually stunning brewing method that uses vacuum filtration to push extremely hot water through a bed of freshly ground coffee. Thanks to a paper filter and a relatively quick extraction time, this technique creates an uncommonly delicate cup.

$SBUX $DNKN pic.twitter.com/7nVtVGNXPp

It's not "just" bankruptcies either. $SBUX closed ~150 stores last year (which was a big uptick in closures).

column32: 4b. There's also a difference btw a drive-thru like $SBUX model vs. opening back up a bar/nightclub or any other business that's inside + crowded. Risk is ~18x higher at indoor crowded places vs. open air. High risk businesses should open up at a later date or limit customers.
column33:
4a. Most important: Type of business vs. ROC.
There's a single digit ROC # that it starts to make more sense to open up. I'm not sure if that's 5%, 1% or 0.1%. But the way to figure it out is to match up when $MCD, $SBUX, $NKE, etc. started to open up in China vs. ROC.
column34:

11/ $SBUX = strong balance sheet, generous dividend, and powerful, beloved global brand which allows it to sell a gazillion cups of overpriced coffee every day

$MCD - Massive scale allows it to price aggressively, decent mobile offering, healthy balance sheet
column28:
8/ As for operating margins, $MCD's franchise business model allows for higher margins here as well.

Given that all its locations are company-owned, $SBUX's op margins are fairly impressive. Selling cups of coffee at a premium isn't the worst business idea.  pic.twitter.com/5IUdnOvSG7
column29: 7/ When looking at these companies' gross profit margins, we once again see the difference between the franchising and company-owned business models. $MCD and $DPZ franchise, while $DRI only has franchise options for int'l locations and $SBUX does not franchise at all.  pic.twitter.com/PyFJNw8J3d
column30:
5/ Of course, we can't just look at growth, we also need to look at valuations, though they're probably all "off" from the disruption the industry is seeing.

$DPZ is a great operator, but are they worth this premium to $MCD and $SBUX? $DRI's valuation seems ... decent? pic.twitter.com/4i3wFOzhlm
column31:
4/ Domino's $DPZ earnings have also skyrocketed the past 5 yrs, +241%!

$MCD and $SBUX have shown steady EPS growth, but was more impressed by Darden's $DRI earnings growth before being decimated by COVID-19. If it can get back to "normal", it might still have lots of room to run pic.twitter.com/g8u6KRmTaE
column32:
3/ Not surprisingly, given it's price appreciation and poll win, $DPZ has grown revenue far faster than the others, but $SBUX has managed respectable rev growth too.

Most surprising? $MCD's revenue has contracted by ~20% over past 5 yrs. pic.twitter.com/dCvAMthaLt
column33:
